        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Copying from https://github.com/neovim/nvim-lspconfig/pull/4140#issuecomment-3426270993 for reference: \n\n> `enable(false)` already calls `:stop()`: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/b67eff38fe19876ab228007897224ec04b58aa40/runtime/lua/vim/lsp.lua#L590-L591\n> \n> oh, but I see this PR adds a `true` arg to \"force\" it.\n> \n> but you can already get \"force\" behavior [by calling `LspStop` twice](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/b67eff38fe19876ab228007897224ec04b58aa40/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/client.lua#L864-L866)? \n> \n> > --- By default, it will just request the server to shutdown without force. If\n> > --- you request to stop a client which has previously been requested to\n> > --- shutdown, it will automatically escalate and force shutdown.\n> \n> \n> If that's not good enough, I suggest sending a PR to Nvim core (and we can backport it to Nvim 0.11) which will automatically \"escalate\" after X seconds, similar to [what we already do on Nvim exit](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/b67eff38fe19876ab228007897224ec04b58aa40/runtime/lua/vim/lsp.lua#L1169-L1172).",
